{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893786/1930112901/0504.xml":{"full_text":"(Dir Inmmsuflk Herald\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter in the Postoffice,\nBrownsville Texas\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nMEMBER OF HIE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Aiscciated Press is exclusively ent!Med to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to It or\nnot otherwise credited m this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nSubscription Kates\u2014Dally and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Year .S9 OG\nSix Months **-50\nThree Months S2i2b\nOne Month. *7s\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representative*\nDallas. Texas 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo., 3U6 Coca-Cola Building.\nChicago, 111., Association Building.\nNew York. 350 Madison Avenue.\nSt. Louis, 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles. CaE, Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg..\n846 S. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Ca!., 318 Kohl Building.\ni\nf i\nBrownsville Has:\n1. A population in 1920 of 22,050.\n2. A mean average temperature of 73.\n2. Bank deposits, $8,000,000.\n4. I our railroads, seven naved highways,\nft. International airport, five air lines.\n6. A $6,000,000 deep water port financed.\n7. The best climate, soil in the world.\n\u201cA Just Judge the Noblest Work\nOf God\u201d\nIt has been said that Justice is sacred and not the\nJudge, but that a just judge is the noblest work of\nGod. It lias likewise been said that flowers for the\nliving is more appropriate than flowers for the cof\nfined clay of an individual who has paid the debt he\nowes nature. A reminder that the Travis County Bar\nassociation banqueted Judge George Calhoun and un\nveiled a portrait ol the distinguished Texas jurist. It\nwas a notable event In the career of a notable man.\nwho has been judge of the 53rd district court since\n1903. with a judicial record unspotted and a private\nlife unstained.\nJudge R. H. Ward of Houston was the principal\nspeaker. He said it all in his foreword, according to\nthose who have followed the career milepost by mile\npost of the guest of honor, \u201cif I were called on to\nselect the foremost citizen, not only of Travis county,\nbut of the state of Texas, I would select Judge George\nCalhoun.'*\nCivilized man should tell of the achievements and\ndeeds and traits of character of an individual in or\noiv of the public service while the subject is In the\nland of the living. Yes. justice and not the judge is\nracrcd and a Just judge is the noblest work of God.\n'Tis well that it is so. Law should ever be uppermost,\njustice should ever be meted out, tempered with\nmercy and the jurist who is Just should receive the\npraise cf his feliowmen.\nValue of an October Dollar\nA W ashington correspondent tells his readers that\nriic American dollar contained 121 cents in October\ni compared with 100 cents four years ago. Further\nmore whether he bought food, clothing, building ma\nterials or drugs, to name a few* miscellaneous pro\nducts, this hypothetical person paid less for them in\nOctober than in the previous months. A survev\nshows that wholesale prices of farm products dropped\nfour per cent while retail prices of food, lagging\nsomewhat, fell only nine-tenths of one per cent.\nThe plain English o? this is that the American dol\nlar in October had a purchasing power of $1,121. Ls\nit going higher and higher?\nMust Come From the Top Down\nBusiness Week is an important trade journal. It\ngives this timely advice editorially: \u201cBusiness revival\ncan come only by buying: buying must come from the\ntop down. To business men we say. forget the centra!\nbank; but pray for energy and enlightenment among\ntheir leaders. Forget the commercial bank, but make\nthem loan you some money to do some buying now.\nWhen, with or without their aid, you have filled your\nquota then and then only look to the man in the\nstreet to fill his. You will then find that you can\nforget all about that, too.'*\nDo you get It?\nBusiness revival must come from the top down.\nThe Once*Over!\nJ By R I. PHILLIPS\nBOBBY JONES APPEARS FOR HIS FIRST\nPICTURE\n(Scene I\u2014Waiting Room of Studio.)\nGirl Attendant\u2014Didja wish to see somebody?\nBobby\u2014Yes, a Mr. Blotz, I think.\nGirl\u2014What's the name?\nBobby\u2014Mr. Jones.\nGirl\u2014What initials?\nBobby\u2014R. T.\nGirl\u2014Artie Jones, yes sir.\nBobby\u2014Ra, Robert Jones.\nGirl (unimpressed by names like Jones, Smith and\nBrown;\u2014What'll I say you want to see him about?\nBobby\u2014It a .out some picture I'm to make.\nGirl *very skeptical;\u2014What's the name of the\npitcher?\nBobby (a little impatiently)\u2014I don't know just yet\nGirl\u2014Are you an actor?\nBobby\u2014Not yet.\nMr. Blotz (chancing to pass through and overhear\ning the name;\u2014Ah, Bobby! Glad to see you! Well,\nwell, well! Step right in. We re all waiting lor you.\nGirl (still in a haze as they disappear)\u2014Jones?\nJones? Well, I never heard of him. He must be one\nof them foreign stars.\n(Scene II \u2014Mr. Biotz\u2019s Office.)\nMr. Blotz\u2014Now, Bobby, brfore we go ahead there\nare a few details of costuming, scenic effects and so\nforth to be decided. I've been talking it over with\nI our costuming department and I don't know whether\nyou should appear in a smart riding suit or evening\ni clothes and silk hat.\nBobby\u2014Why, it's a golf lesson. I ll wear golf\nclothes.\nMi-. Blotz (in horror)\u2014Oh, no. That would never\ndo. This is to be a feature picture, of course. It\nwill be a real production. In fact, seme of the of\nficials think you should appear in oriental attire, as\nthe rajah of the links, you know. It would be very\nspectacular, and get the women.\nBobby\u2014But after all I'm a golfer and\nMr. Blotz-Tush! You're much more than a golf\ner, Mr. Jones. You are the king of golfers.\nThat's an idea! Why rot dress you as a king? i\nDiamond-studded crown, ermine robes and\neverything! Audiences love that king stuff\nand\nBobby\u2014But. Mr. Blotz, as a golfer I\nMr. Blotz\u2014And I don't know whether to have you\nmake your first appeal ance cn horseback or by\nRolls-Royce. Some of the boys have suggested an air- j\nplane. If you come in as a king you could make a\ngrand entrance on an elephant .We have a\ntroup of elephants that we just used in \u2022Flaming\nMahatmas.\u201d\nBobby (quite depressed by it all)\u2014It's to be an illu\nstration of golf and I think all I should do is appear\nin regular golf clothes and\nMr. Blotz\u2014That would never do. It's simply not\ngood picture stuff. We mustn't let the people think\nyou are just a golfer. You must be something much\ngreater, much more imposing. Now about caddies\nBobby\u2014I have a caddy and\nMr. Blotz\u2014One faddy, Mr. Jones! Don't be ridicu\nlous. This company will give you a vast army of\ncaddies. There will be 300 of them, all gorgeously\nrobed. One of our authors has written a pageant for\nthem. They come in on Arabian horses. Behind j\nthem are eighteen sacred oxen bearing your golf\nballs.\nBobby <rather sick \u2014But, as a golfer, I think\nMr. Blctz\u2014And after the pageant there is a blare\nof trumpets. Our super chorus of 250 girls come on\nstrewing flowers and then you enter to the cheers\nof the populace and\nMr. Goldhammer (scenic chief, interrupting*\u2014Oh.!\ner. Mr. Blotz. About that setting for the Jones les\nsons.\nMr. Blotz\u2014Yes.\nMr. Goldhammer\u2014We've decided to have an en\normous pool in the background with 36 fountains\nplaying and a lot of bathing girls swimming around.\nOff to the right there will be a castle with 16 Russian\nwolfhounds on the steps. Mr. Jones will give his\ngolf lessons on a great stairway atop of which will be\nLeo Pitalvy s jazz band of 63 pieces and\nMr. Blotz\u2014What do you think of that. Mr. Jones?\n(He turns and notices that Bobby has disappeared. j\n(Scene III.\u2014The Reception Room.)\nMr. Blotz (rushing out)\u2014Where did Mr. Jones go?\nWhere did Mr. Jones go?\nGirl Attendant\u2014That guy Artie Jones? He just\njumped outa the window!\nIt's All Clear Now\nThe American Bar Association has voted for pro\nhibition repeal by two to one. Explaining perhaps\nwhy the court cry is \u201cOrder! Order!\u201d\nOur Boarding House By Ahern\n\nrODVS Fl5H7\u201cTWoR\\rTb^, hauifullv soppy Aki 111\nT -r\u00abooo^-r YOU hawwju.y sorry, po VaU harm\nWePE PREPARED CLP MAM\u2019 BLrr -fo PR^-P^CK\nvjcre P2fFA,^r c my tawmcy is for owe migh-tj\nOLi\"^ -fo A-^ -fflg .w-fiT PEA SOW YOU\nME \"THIS EYEMlMG HEARTH To.MIGHT DowV BELiEUE OUR\nEGAD DoMT You AMD READ \u201cTHE CEMSUS REPORTEOR\nRECALL ME SAV'MG J> PIPER! BESIDES, -fti5 CrfY IS BECAUSE\ni \u201cTHERE VO A 5 \"to BE j MpTolR v/OUR PACE ALL YOU\u2019V/E SEEM\nV A Smoker awl U is a BiT-roo fast itFsR Tujemttv nears^\nPOOL-TbuRMAMEM-F T. 'FbR PellyJ 7 ARE miu<-mem am\nATTHE ClWL^S CLUB Jy I CAVOMY STAY I\nTomigHT? Hup Tll DawM ?^2si\nlike am \u2019gvwlimg\no \u25a0Hcr ._.\nC i \u00bbaojr>_\u00bb\u00bbc* senvict me.\n5{!e Has -to\nSlWOl.E-TFOcn' -TOUiOri-T.\n;-f\nSunday School Lesson\n\nMAKING BUSINESS CHRISTIAN\n_ ___ I 1\nText: Luke 13:1-10\nAnd Jesus entered and passed\nthrough Jericho.\nAnd. behold, there was a man\nnamed Zaecheus, which was the\nchief among the publicans, and he\nwas rich.\nAil\u2019d he sought to see Jesus who\nhe was: and could not for the\npress, because he was little of\nstature.\nAnd lie ran before, nnd climbed\nup into a sycamore tree to sec\nhim; for he was to pass that way.\nAnd when Jesus came to the\nplace, he looked up. and saw him.\nand said unto him. Zaecheus, make\nhaste, and come down; for today I\nmust abide at thy house.\nAnd he made haste, and came\ndown, and received him joyfully.\nAnd when they ^aw it. they all j\nmurmured, saying, That he was 1\ncone to be guest with a man that\n13 a sinner.\nAnd Zaccheus stood, and said\nunto the Lord: Behold. Lord, the\nhalf of *ny goods I give to the poor:\nand if I have taken anvthine from\nany man by fals* accusation, I res-\ntore him fourfold.\nAnd Jesus sa;d unfo him. This\nday is salvation come to this h use\nforasmuch as he also is a son of\nAbraham.\nFor the Son of man Is '\u2022omp to\nr-r\u2018r-'-~ and to save that w! h was\nlost.\nThe International I'niform Sunday\nSchorl Lesson for November SO.\nMaking Business Christian. Luke\n19:1-10.\nBY \\VM. L. GILROY. O. D.\nI.ditor of The CongregatlcnaHst\nNo better lesson upon the theme\nof \u201cmaking business Christian\u201d\ncould be chosen than this story of\nZacchaeus. for whatever interpreta\ntion we place upon the story Zac\nchaeus stands as a great example\nof the business man consecrating\nhimself and his wealth to high\nChristian ends.\nIf Zacchaeus all a\u2019or.e had been\nstriving earnestly and faithfully to\nconduct his course honestly and\nfairly in a profession which w-a*\ngiven over extortion and dishon\nesty. tha*: example strongly com\nmends him.\nWhereas if Zacchaeus or the\nother hand has been unjust and ex- i\ntortionate the completeness of his\nteadiness to make restitution marks\nin the surest and most definite wav\nthe sort of revolution that alone\ncan establish Christian conditions\nwhere formerly conditions of self\nishness and evil prevailed.\nThese two interpretations, it\nshould be stated, have been nlaced\nupon the storv as It reflects the\ncharacter and former course of\nZacchaeus. For the conception that\nZaechseus had all along been a\nman striving in an unpopular and\nmorally dangerous calling to con\nduct himself honorably, the finest\nstatement is to be found in a great\nsermon by Frederick W. Robertson\nof Brighten, on Hindrances Over\ncome.\nTried to Live Right\nThis great preacher of the last j\ncentury in that brilliant and power- i\nfu! sermon defends Zacchaeus\nagainst the Imputations that have I\nbeen made against his character.\nHe represents him as a man who\nthrough his unpopular calling as\ntax gatherer for the Romans, and\npossibly in some other way. had be\ncome overwhelmed with an evil re\nputation. yet who. in snite of that\nrenutation and with a its over\nwhelming handicaps, had striven to\nlive honestly and according to his\nbest Ideals.\nThe\u2019> is much warrant for that\nrepresentation, for if Zacchaeus\nhad been a pumoseful extortioner,\nhe could hardly have restored four\nfold the things tha* he had taken\nfrom the people dishonestly.\nThe natural conclusion would V>\nthat his very statement. \u201cIf I have\ntaken anything from any men bv\nfalse accusation,\u201d suggested that he j\nwas not conscious of having done\nso. but that If he had in anv wav\noverlooked anv evtnrtionate action,\nhe had the strong purpose to make\nthe matter right.\nAccording to the Jewish law*, the\nrestoring four-fold of anything tak\n1 1\n___ I\nNEW YO*tK, Nov. 28\u2014The name\nlooming largest at the moment on\nthe Broadway skyline is that of\nMaxwell Anderson.\nAnderson\u2019s latest play, 'Elizabet\nthe Queen,\u201d which the Theater\nGuild is presenting, has been greet\ned with critical prophesies to \"the\neffect chat it will be one of the few\ncontemporary dramas likely to be\nheard from 20 years hence. That's\nn long time in piaydom's memory,\nif you asked me.\nAnd if this be so, no playwright\nhas been more patient or persever\ning in struggling toward his even\n;ual achievement. Certainly few liv\n,ng writers have been more definit\n,y independent in their attitude to\nward the stage. He has insisted on\nkeeping the poetic aspect in the\nface of all theatrical temptat.ons to\n;et the \u201cquick money.\u201d\n\nWhen I first encountered Ander\nson, he was writing editorials on a\nSan Francisco newspaper. His op\nportunities for expression be*ng\nthwarted, he chnged papers, only to\nrun afoul of s/milar dictations a\nfew blocks away. In the end. he\npacked up and headed east.\nFor a time Anderson was asso\nriated with a poetry magazine, but\nno such berth was ever known to\n->ay the rent. He went about through\nnewspapers and magazines and\nthen suddenly reappeared as co\nauthor with Lawrence Stallings of\nWhat Price Glory?\u201d It was, as\njveryone knows, a great hit. Yet,\nsomehow. the name of Stallings be\n\u2022amc attached to It, and Ander\nson appeared in the light of an al\nso-ran.\nAnderson, meanwhile, had moved\nvis family to a low-nricr Bronx flat\n\u25a0Uiere they were all but doubling tin\n:o keen expenses down That's all\n\u2022hanged now. He has an estate in\nhe country, a place in Hollovwood\nfor his movie moments and a New\nStickler So 1 ution I\nThe apple man has 14 apples,\nof which Willie got half of 14,\nplus 1. or 8; Tommy got half of\nthe remaining 6. plus I. or 4. and\nJohnny got half of the remaining\n'L plus I. or 2. .The man thus had i\nnone left. i\nYork dwelling place. But these came\nonly through struggle.\n\nFrom his Bronx w indog, Ander\nson gained the material lor \"Sat- 1\nurday's Children\u201d\u2014a splendid por\ntrait of its kind, but not a commer\ncial success. \"Outside Looking In\u201d\nadded to his prestige, but only\nslightly to his pocketbook. \"Gypsy\nand another drama about th<. Sac\nco-Vanzetti case came along. They\nwere all variously too bitter, too\nironic or poetic for the big box of\nfice.\nNow comes a public admission of\nhis standing as one of the very bet\nter playwrights. The moral of nil\nwhich is just abcut what any strug\ngling young plavw right wishes to\nmake it.\n\nAnd speaking of playfolk. a note\ncomes to hand announcing that\nFarl Carroll has invented some new\ngadget by which necessary paint\nntay be sprinkled upon the actresses\nand chorines.\nThis Carroll always is showing\nup with some tricky device. He is\ni known chiefly as a producer who\nseems to be in jail-houses and\ncourt-houses for breach of good\ntaste, yet his role as a theatrical\ntechnician and inventor may some\nday make the man-on-the-street\ni recognize this other side of the\nman.\nIt was Carroll, for Instance, who\ninvented the tricky disappearing\norchestra pits. And the new theater\nI he is building in Fiftieth street w ill\nbe filled with Carroll^scue contrap\nlens. He has figured out a wav of\n'seating 3ooo persons while still\nkeeping them comfortable, -a ha\u2019f\ndozen back-stare labor saving de\nvices and a trick lighting system\nwhich ha\u00ab real novelty. There does\nnot for instance, anpear to be a\nringle lighting fixture in the place,\nthe result beine obtained by reaction\nagainst a certain metal.\nAny desired color or color com\nbination can be obtained by this\n\"ejection system. His movable or\nchestra platform has been perfected\nto allow three different levels and\nthree different band stands.\nThe pain* spraying device is an\nair brush which can coat with col\nor the flesh of r.ny chorine; now a\nlaborious Job of hand work.\nr en unjustly was the obligation of a\nthief, and Zacchea\u2019us was facing the\nsituation courageously and honestly\nby saying virtually, \u201cIX I have used\nmy office for extortion. I have been\na thief, and I resore the thief s\nportion.''\nWhatever interpretation we put\nupon the incident, the one striking\nthing is that Zacchaeus in his meet\ning of Jesus found the true triumph\nof ail that was best in him. Wheth\ncr Jesus was vindicating the moral\npurpose that Zaachaeus had dis\nplayed all along and was bringing\nthat former purpose to its supreme\nplace, or whether Jesus in that\nmoment beneath the tree brought\nto Zaachaeus the glorious vision of\na transformed life, the resulting\nexperience was all that Christ\nian privilege can suggest.\nZacchaeus, a man of small physical\nstature, stands forth as a man of\ngiant-like proportions in his moral\nand religious life.\nAll Can Be Saved\nThe salvation that Jesus brought\nto the house of Zacchaeus is the\nsalvation that he can bring to every\nhouse and to every individual. The\nnotion that business cannot be\ntouched with righteousness and\ntruth is economically as wrong and\nunsound as it is morally. More and\nmore we arc discovering that. This\ndoes not mean that there are not\nissues in business life where a man\nhas to choose very definitely be\ntween a right course of action and\nprobable, or certa.n, economic loss.\nMore than one individual has\nbeen compelled to make such cru\ncial decisions, and it is no more i\ntrue that the loss that men have\nbeen willing to accept for righteous-\nness sake has had some correspond\ning economic gain than it is true\nthat the way of the cross for Jesus\nwas not a way of real loss.\nWhat is true is that as in the\ncase of the Master's going to the\ncross, so with every man who in\nbusiness refuses even for the sake\nof gain to do something dishonest\nor dishonorable, there is something\nof the resurrection triumph. No\ngain can compensate for the loss of\na man's self-respect or any gain in\nfortune for the death of his soul.\n_ j\nIMM ACIT-ATE COM EPI ION\nCHUKdl\nJefferson and 12th Street\nSunday Masses ai 6:30 7:30, 'J and\n10 o'clock. The ten o'clock Is the\nchildren's mass. Sur.oav school at\nj eleven o'clock.\nSunday evening services at 7.30\nRosary and benediction\nMasses on week-days at 6:30 and\n7 o'clock.\nThursdays and Fridays at 4 p m.\nChristian doctrine for children not\nof our schools.\nThursday evening at 7:30, Holy\nHour. f\nThe week beginning Sunday, Nov.\n2 to Nov. 10 is in honor of poor\nsouls. Sermon each evening of no\nvena. Masses on first Fridays at 6\nand 7 o'clock, evening services with\nsermon a' 7:30. Confessions on the\nafternoons of Saturdays and the\nvigils of feasts.\nRev. Joseph Rose, O. M. L\nPastor.\nFIRST METHODIST CHURCH\n9 30\u2014Sunday school. W W.\nUnderwood, superintendent. There\narc classes for all ages. The Busi\nness Men's Bible class, which meets\nat the Queen theatre at 9:45 a. m\nwill be favored with special vocal\nmusic by the men's quartet Sunday\nmorning and all men not attending\nRev. H. J. Howard will speak on\nvited\n10:50 a m\u2014Preaching by pastor.\n6:30 p. m \u2014Epworth Leagues